{"author":"Iso Tester","data":{"body":"PLAN REVIEW · PASS 1 · [T1] Prior-art / novel-architecture justification (overlay) — VERDICT: 1 finding (the rest of the bright-line surface PASSES with prior art well-handled).\n\nBright lines that fire here: external integration (Inspect AI eval harness; CI with live LLM provider calls), a migration (\"unify LLM functionality on the engine\"), and a novel pattern (context-injection solver + stubbed repo tools for the agentic reviewers; two-tier eval model; three-pass review). Most of these are PASSES — see affirmations — because the patterns are already established in-repo (src/rebar/llm/eval.py) and the plan/child build on them rather than reinventing. The single open T1 item is the one genuinely new mechanism that no prior art covers and whose enabling Inspect capability is asserted but unresolved.\n\nFINDINGS (T1):\n\n- [ ] Resolve the unverified Inspect-AI capability assertion underlying AC5's \"context-injection solver plus stubbed or fixture-backed repo tools\" before committing the design. (criteria: T1) — AC5 requires the three store/repo-coupled agentic reviewers to run under Inspect via a solver that injects repo/store context and stubs or fixture-backs the repo TOOLS. This mechanism does not exist anywhere in the codebase yet (search for `solver`/`context-injection` under src/rebar/llm returns only the comment placeholder at eval.py:342; eval.py:341-346 explicitly leaves the live Task wiring `dataset → solver(prompt) → scorers → epochs` unbuilt and `run_eval()` raising NotImplementedError). T1(c) asks that \"library supports X\" assertions be resolved: the load-bearing assertion is that Inspect's solver/tool API actually supports injecting per-sample context AND swapping the reviewer's repo-tool implementations for stubs/fixtures at eval time. Pin this to a concrete Inspect API (e.g. which solver primitive and which tool-override seam, at the INSPECT_MIN_VERSION 0.3.221 floor in eval.py:40) so the design isn't committed on an unverified capability.\n  location: AC line 5 (\"`run_eval()` runs a real Inspect eval … context-injection solver plus stubbed or fixture-backed repo tools\"); child rink-cloud-gum Phase-2.2/2.5; src/rebar/llm/eval.py:40,319-351\n  evidence: [\n    \"AC5: 'the three store/repo-coupled agentic reviewers run via a context-injection solver plus stubbed or fixture-backed repo tools'\",\n    \"ABSENCE: no solver/context-injection implementation exists (search_files `solver`/`context-injection` under src/rebar/llm yields only eval.py:342 placeholder comment); run_eval() still raises NotImplementedError (eval.py:346)\",\n    \"eval.py:40 pins INSPECT_MIN_VERSION = '0.3.221' as the API floor, but the solver/tool-override capability that AC5 depends on is named, not verified against that API\",\n    \"child rink-cloud-gum 'Why': 'the 3 reviewers read the store + repo via tools, so they are NOT inline-feedable' — i.e. the design hinges on tool-stubbing being achievable in Inspect\"\n  ]\n  suggested_fix: In AC5 (or the child's Phase-2.2 task), name the concrete Inspect AI primitive(s) the solver uses to (1) inject per-sample repo/store context into the reviewer transcript and (2) substitute stub/fixture repo-tool implementations for the live ones, and confirm those exist at the 0.3.221 floor. If the tool-override seam is not first-class in Inspect, capture the fallback (e.g. wrapping the reviewer behind a rebar-side tool registry that the eval swaps) so the design is not committed on an unconfirmed library capability.\n\nAFFIRMATIONS (T1 criteria already satisfied — emitted as positive feedback, not findings):\n- Prior art for the eval seam is CONSIDERED, not reinvented: the plan extends the existing Inspect-AI machinery in src/rebar/llm/eval.py (grader discipline, Cohen's-kappa judge alignment, at_least(k) gate with banned pass@k, promptfoo/JUnit interop, the 4 packaged specs) to 7 specs rather than building a parallel harness — AC3/AC4 and child rink-cloud-gum's \"all 7 specs\" reconcile to 4 existing + 3 new.\n- The two-tier eval model (zero-cost deterministic gate every PR + non-blocking, cached, concurrency-capped, fork-safe live tier on dispatch/weekly schedule) is a well-trodden CI pattern, not a novel architecture — no prior-art search owed (anti-FP); the child explicitly notes alignment with community consensus.\n- The migration's prior art is cited rather than re-litigated: WS-MIGRATE/WS-PROMPTS/WS-CLEANUP/WS-VISUAL/WS-VALIDATE/WS-INTENT-ALIGN are recorded as DONE via closed sibling epics (5766/72d5/e6d9), and the earlier open-ended decisions (DSL map/fan-out, cleanup set, visual-format choice) are stated as already settled there — no reinvention in this epic.\n- The grader-discipline rules (cross-family judge, gates:false, pinned dated snapshot, coverage threshold, non-empty gold_set) in AC3 mirror the established validate_scorer/validate_eval_spec contract already in eval.py — repackaging of an in-repo standard, correctly reused.\n- The three-pass review pattern and llm-framework seam referenced for docs (AC2) are existing, documented artifacts (docs/llm-framework.md, docs/plan-review-gate.md) the plan cross-links rather than re-derives."},"env_id":"ade0f2ef-51cc-45a2-bb97-c09846cd3df5","event_type":"COMMENT","timestamp":1782579555513663001,"uuid":"cba4e22d-8cdf-442b-9490-4bb6d5851264"}